    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName><name key="Auge">Auge</name></persName> <g type="apex"/>,
                    <lb n="2"/><expan><abbr>n</abbr><ex>umerus</ex></expan> <num type="cardinal" value="35">XXXV</num>.
                </ab></div>
            
            <div type="translation">
            <p>“Auge, (niche) number 35”</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>Line 1: the apex following Auge is either a punctuation mark or ornamental
                    decoration. Line 2: an interpunct can clearly be seen between ṇ and XXXV; most
                    of the previous readings have interpreted the traces of ṇ as the ending of
                    ann(is), e.g. Van Buren 1927, Ohl 1931, AE 1993, and the AAR entry which give
                    the transcription and translation as Auge ((apex)) | [q(uae) v(ixit) an]n(is)
                    XXXV, “Auge, [who lived for] 35 [years].” In volume 18 of MGR, S. Crea advances
                    a strong argument for reading ṇ as an abbreviation of numerus rather than annis
                    and I follow her interpretation here. Rather than indicating the age of the
                    deceased, XXXV is the location of her niche in a communal columbarium (cf. CIL
                    6.7997-8011); moreover, an apex mirroring the one still extant on the right side
                    could have existed on the left side before the slab broken in antiquity and
                    reused for Cliens, and this would have perfectly balanced the brief, two-line
                    inscription. The lettering is impressively stylized and consistent throughout,
                    serifs are carefully flourished and the lettering height is diligently uniform
                    in both lines (though of two different heights), and the carver’s attempt at
                    shading can best be seen in the A, U, and G of line 1. 
                    </p>
                <p>
                    An epitaphic columbarium
                    tablet for Auge, a person perhaps of servile origin given that her tablet was
                    reused in antiquity by a person also of likely servile status, Volumnia
                    Symposia, for the tomb of her husband, Cliens, who was probably a slave at the
                    time of his death (see USEP commentary of the obverse inscription referenced
                    above). Auge is a relatively common Greek name in Roman contexts, Solin counted
                    101 instances in his survey (cf. p. 1441). On paleographic grounds, the
                    inscription can be dated to the first century C.E., and it must have been
                    inscribed and probably relatively long (one or two generations) before it was
                    reused for Cliens’ columbarium which can be dated to the first century C.E. </p></div>
            

